 bosonic modes confined with multiple tunneling-coupled cavities, with Fig. 1 showcasing an example with three cavities in a triangular configuration. Assuming a_{n}^{{\\dagger}} and a_{n} are the creation and annihilation operators of the n th cavity mode respectively, the tight-binding Hamiltonian of such spin-cavity system is given by [EQUATION] where \\omega_{n} is the resonance frequency of photon mode in the n th cavity with a periodic boundary condition a_{N_{c}+1}=a_{1} ( N_{c}=3 as an example to elaborate on our theoretical calculations below), and J is the photon hopping strength. The collective spin operators S_{\\alpha}=\\sum_{j=1}^{N}\\sigma_{\\alpha}^{j}/2 ( \\alpha=x,y,z ) are defined by using the individual Pauli spin operators \\sigma_{\\alpha}^{j} , where j denotes the j th two-level emitter. At the n th cavity site, the local spin-cavity coupling strength is characterized by g .", "equation": "+\\hbar\\Omega S_{z}+\\sum_{n=1}^{N_{c}}\\frac{2\\hbar g}{\\sqrt{N}}\\left(a_{n}+a_{n}^{{\\dagger}}\\right)S_{x}\\text{,}", "has_answer": true, "start": 768, "end": 820}
